      <details>
        <summary>How is the P/E ratio calculated?</summary>
        <p>The P/E ratio is calculated by dividing a company's current stock price by its Earnings Per Share (EPS).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the difference between Forward and Trailing P/E?</summary>
        <p>Trailing P/E uses historical earnings from the past 12 months, while Forward P/E uses projected, estimated earnings for the next 12 months.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is a lower P/E ratio always better?</summary>
        <p>Not necessarily. While a low P/E might indicate a stock is undervalued, it could also signal a 'value trap' where the market correctly expects the company's earnings to decline. Conversely, a high P/E might be justified by rapid growth.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
